The continual repetition of the chorus at the end of the song can come across as an enchanting, hypnotic chant which conveys the lyrical theme of drunkenness.

It’s all honey, honey
 It’s all honey
 It’s all honey, honey
 It’s all honey

As stated in the YouTube live stream after the Honey music video premiere, Samia said Honey was originally written as a slow, sad song. Her producer Caleb suggested trying a version of it that was more sonically upbeat, that way it can take on a double meaning.

The lyrics and the song are about “being drunk and in denial” but Samia thinks it’s cool that the song has also taken on another meaning with listeners that has turned her difficult experience into art that can be used to express happy moments as well.

The juxtaposition in the two moods is interesting and can change the way you interpret the song: to one, the chorus can be like a happy campfire song with friends. But it can also come across as an enchanting, hypnotic chant which conveys the lyrical theme of drunkenness.

From under here, all you can fear is being
 Saved and being wakeful
According to Samia, these lyrics describe the feeling “when you’re drunk and the worst thing you can imagine is being sober again”
We’re singing along, “Can you do no harm?”
Samia further embeds Porches into the storyline, quoting their 2018 song “Country”.
All you can do when he needs you is close your eyes

In Instagram posts promoting the songs “Honey” and “Breathing Song,” Samia said that the two songs “tell the same story” and are “about the same thing.” This line may be a euphemism for sexual assault or coercion, a theme of “Breathing Song.” Here, the man’s sexual desire is described as a “need.” The words “all you can do” reflect feeling powerless when attempts to get him to change his mind fail; Samia resorts instead to closing her eyes.

Do you wanna go to Baby’s?
 It’s been a long week and I don’t want to think
 And Porches is playing

Baby’s All Right is a bar and music venue in Brooklyn, New York. Many local acts like Porches have performed there, along with global stars. Samia herself performed at the venue in celebration of the release of Honey.

As of the time of song’s release, Porches' two most recent shows at Baby’s were on October 2, 2022 and November 7, 2018.

It’s all honey, honey
 It’s all honey
 It’s all honey, honey

“The whole record is about trying to achieve that drunken honey feeling without painful relationships and alcohol.”
All you can do from this hotel room is fantasize
“I want [the song] to be whichever thing anybody needs when they’re listening to it. It feels hopeful to me and hope is the saddest feeling of all."

Whatever you want, it’s at the bar
 Nobody’s gonna tell you who you are

In a letter sent out with preordered vinyls of Samia’s album Honey she writes, “[The song is] about a time in my life where I was drinking every day to distract myself from the pain but it doesn’t sound like that. It sounds like a campfire singalong."

description.plain:
Samia explores her fear of conflict in “Big Wheel,” singing about frustrations she faced in relationships. The track was the second release from her debut album, The Baby, paired with “Stellate” as a B-side.

Upon the track’s release, Samia told Fader:

I wrote it after a few hours of laying in bed imagining hypothetical conversations with people that I was too scared to have in real life. It’s a passive confession of harbored resentments buried in a laundry list of gratitude.

annotations: And my mama in the night
Samia’s mama is actress Kathy Najimy.
I got bug bites on my legs
This lyric feeds into the theme of allowing uncomfortableness, of allowing people to hurt you.

I got a lover in my bedroom
 Or the smell of him at least
 If he’s somewhere getting smarter
 On a free man’s odyssey
 God, I’m really gonna blow
 With all this empathetic shit
 I understand the thing you did
 And every reason you did it
 But I’m so mad dude
 And I wanna cry
 I got bad news but I didn’t fight

Her lover has left her, and she is left with only the traces of him. She imagines what he’s doing now that he’s left her. She understands why he left her, but it still hurts. She seems to be angry that she didn’t try harder to make their relationship work.
I got two friends who look alike

These two friends are fellow musician Raffaella and actress Olivia Nikkanen.



 Oliva & Raffaella 

All three women spent their teenage years in New York City, sharing mutual friends and social circles. One of their first publicly documented pictures together appeared on Raffaella’s Instagram in early 2018, although photos of  Olivia and herself indicate that they had already known each other for several years.

Samia has confirmed that this line is about Oliva and Raffaella, posting a TikTok featuring their image and also sharing a picture of the pair on her Instagram story:
I got a big wheel in Montana
A “big wheel” is slang for an influential or important person.

annotations: I’m thinking about Texas
This likely refers to Texas’s “trigger law” banning abortion in response to the overturning of Roe v. Wade in June 2022.

And I’ll fucking kill her
 And I’ll fucking freak out
“The killing is just a demonstration. Look at everything I can feel."

I’ve never been this bad
 Can I tell you something?
 I’ve never felt so unworthy of loving

In a letter sent out with preordered vinyls of Samia’s album Honey she writes, “I wrote this about withholding and then exploding. It’s not even about jealousy. I never said how I really felt because I didn’t wanna scare them away. I tried to become them so they would want me around. I just couldn’t do it for very long – I got tired and I was so lonely.”

And when you get passive, I like to imagine
 You listening to worship songs on your iPod
This line compliments the almost religious organ, that plays throughout this song, especially in the beginning.

I thought about lying when I found my passport
 ’Cause I would’ve stayed kinda drunk and afraid
 In your room ’til I died in your room if you asked for it

This lyric encapsulates what it is to love someone so much that you would give up anything to get to be around them. In this case, she’s willing to give up her only form of ID, as long as it means she gets to spend time with this boy.

I’ve got a letter still in my backpack
 It’s from the St. Paul Police Department

Whilst she was recording her debut album The Baby, Samia spent several weeks in Minnesota (at the time she lived in NYC). One track from the album sees her contemplate a trip to Minnesota:

Fuck my feet, I’m trying to cross the street but they keep
Going to Minnesota, huh?
I guess I’m going to Minnesota, huh?

Her 2021 song “Elephant” also sees her sing about being drunk in the Twin Cities:

Last time I was drunk in Minneapolis
I swore I wouldn’t end up here again
Essentially, the drunkenness just happens
In minutes from the moment that you land

annotations:
What if we could shut up for an hour or two
 Quiet, memorizing what the people do
 Wouldn’t have to try and find myself in you
Longing for a break in conversation, to rest and people watch, because it is a break from looking for similarities with another person.

You are so disarming with your honest smile
 Tepidly confessing that you swallowed a fly
These lines make me think of her current boyfriend, Briston Maroney who’s Instagram bio is literally “I swallowed a bug once”.

Getting all lit up about the outdoor malls
 Baby, let me show you the synthetic pond

Samia shares how her or her crush is so excited talking about a mall that is possibly LA’s The Grove, with the following line playfully describing mall music against beauty that imitates nature but was made by men
I just saw my whole life flash before your eyes

perhaps this refers to the death of the other person’s perception of Samia rather than her real self. trying to “charm” someone only works as long as you can maintain the facade, and here Samia may be alluding to the fear that a minor slip up could bring the whole charade crashing down.

Couldn’t we believe it was the hand of God
 Making water boogie to a Kesha song

Samia immediately introduces us to the juxtaposition of this song: illusion vs. reality. though it’s tempting to buy in to the idea that the water is moving magically, it’s clear this is a deliberately crafted illusion.

similarly, Samia alludes to the temptation to “charm,” but is reluctant to do so “this time.”

description.plain:
“Is There Something In The Movies” discusses Samia’s disillusionment with the entertainment industry, especially in reference to the death of actress Brittany Murphy.

In February 2020, a video posted by Caleb Hinz (Normal Parents) showed Samia colouring in an album checklist, featuring a song titled “Movies.”

A collection of photos featuring Samia, her bandmates, Caleb, and members of Hippo Campus in the studio were posted to her Instagram in December 2019, with the caption:

i’ll do the movie

On April 27, Samia announced that the track would be released that week, on April 29.

annotations: Somebody gave you a knife for your birthday
According to a still very widespread superstition, giving a knife as a gift can bring bad luck, or “cut” the friendship between the blade giver and the recipient.
So I dance down the street

Samia also encourages herself to “dance until you quit” in earlier track “Limbo Bitch”, a song about performing confidence for a lover; here, however, dancing is not performative but a sign of her love for herself.

We’re in a tin box and I’ve got a toothpick
 And I have been poking the air
Samia explains this lyric on her twitter: “i’m performing an effort to get us out of this tin box (bad situation) using a tool that i know will not get us out of this tin box.”

So here, now you’re deathless in art
 You’ve got this and the movies and also my love
 You can have it all, baby, I’m giving it up

Samia is immortalizing Brittany Murphy in this song, which is why she becomes “deathless” in “art” (the song). But Samia continues, that she is also “deathless” in “the movies” because Brittany lives on whenever someone watches Clueless or another of her movies. Samia said that this song is about being disillusioned with the idea of “legacy” in Hollywood, which is why she follows up with “also my love.” While Brittany Murphy’s legacy to most people is her movies, and to fans of Samia, this song, Samia remembers Brittany as someone she loved, the woman she trusted enough to give her her stuffed pig. This is why she has written the song. And in “giving it up,” she is sharing this more human side of Brittany with the world.

Samia has dealt with the theme of remembering a loved one “in art” in her song Triptych, which references the artist Francis Bacon, who painted a triptych of his late lover, George Dyer.

https://americansongwriter.com/the-baby-samia-album-interview/
Miss Angelina
Samia mentioned in a concert of hers that this lyric refers to her old dance teacher, Miss Angelina

And I’m not afraid that if I am the skipper
 I’ll steer my flesh into the bog

Maybe a reference to William Ernest Henley’s poem Invictus https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/51642/invictus
“I am the master of my fate,
I am the captain of my soul.”
And everyone dies but they shouldn’t die young

Brittany Murphy died tragically young at age 32, in an accident attributed by the coroner to pneumonia, iron deficiency and drug intoxication.

American women are expected to live until their late seventies to early eighties, so Murphy’s life was cut extremely short.

I carried around a stuffed pig in my arms
 And I did it until I was five
 I got it from someone who died of attention
 And lived an extraordinary life

This stuffed pig was given to Samia as a baby by the late Brittany Murphy. Brittany died in December 2009, at the age of 32, due to pneumonia and anemia, according to the coroner. During her career as an actress, she worked alongside Samia’s mother,
Kathy Najimy in the series King of the Hill.

In an April 2020 interview, Samia briefly touched on Brittany’s death:

Glorifying the idea of legacy or life as a means to an end makes me really sad, especially when it comes to people dying young […] her death has always felt painfully unnecessary to me and has fueled my resentment towards that whole thing.

annotations: And listened to MUNA at dawn

The Muna record that came out last year, also hugely influenced me. I just liked their bravery and confessional storytelling and I haven’t heard that in a really long time.
